  "distance": "302.692 km (188.084 miles)",
  "event_preview": "Red Bull Ring measures 4.318 km (2.688 mi) and features 10 turns in Spielberg, in the Styrian mountains of Austria. Originally built in 1969 as the legendary Österreichring, the track was completely rebuilt by Hermann Tilke in 1996 and reopened under the Red Bull name in 2014 — retaining the dramatic elevation changes and three sweeping straights of its predecessor while adding the tight infield complex that has since become a prime overtaking arena. One of the shortest and fastest circuits on the calendar, it demands a delicate compromise between low-drag straight-line speed and enough downforce to cope with the high-speed Turns 3 and 4 at the top of the hill. The layout is deceptively simple but ruthless in exposing understeer and poor traction, with Turn 9 — named after Austria's posthumous 1970 World Champion Jochen Rindt — among the most demanding corners of the season. The official race lap record stands at 1:05.619, set by Carlos Sainz Jr for McLaren during the 2020 Styrian Grand Prix, while the all-time qualifying lap record belongs to Valtteri Bottas, who clocked a 1:02.939 for Mercedes in Q3 of the 2020 Austrian Grand Prix weekend.",
  "tyre_compounds": "Tyre supplier Pirelli brought the C3, C4, and C5 tyre compounds.",
